Thank you [~snemeth] for the patch! I have some comment, but I am not entirely sure if this could be done in this patch.
 * First is simple. I would advise to use ParentQueue's QueueCapacityType(it has the weight mode) in CapacitySchedulerInfoHelper#getMode. That said, QueueCapacityType and AbstractCSQueue.CapacityConfigType is almost a same, we might need to merge them together. I would advise to store its string representation in a similar fashion:

{code:java}
private enum QueueCapacityType {
  WEIGHT("weight"),
  ABSOLUTE_RESOURCE("absolute"),
  PERCENT("percentage");

  private String internal;

  QueueCapacityType(String internal) {
    this.internal = internal;
  }

  @Override
  public String toString() {
    return internal;
  }

}
{code}

 * I think this is a more serious issue, and we should think about it. The way getMode discovers the mode might be problematic. Dynamic queues do not have a weight mode config, therefore they will be considered as they were in weight mode. There is a method ParentQueue#getCapacityConfigurationTypeForQueues that is used internally, and handles all corner cases as well. My suggestion would be to put it in AbstractCSQueue and use it instead.

While ParentQueue#getCapacityConfigurationTypeForQueues has a Collection<CSQueue> signature, it is used for single queues as well, by calling it:
{code:java}
getCapacityConfigurationTypeForQueues(ImmutableList.of(queue))
{code}

I just have very minor nits:

#1
{noformat}
config.set(YarnConfiguration.SCHEDULER_CONFIGURATION_STORE_CLASS,
	        YarnConfiguration.MEMORY_CONFIGURATION_STORE);
{noformat}
This call is repeated multiple times, this could be set somewhere else.

 

#2
{noformat}
validateSchedulerInfo(json, "weight", "root.default", "root.test1", "root.test2");
{noformat}
"root.default", "root.test1" and "root.test2" are the same in all cases, you might want to drop them

 

#3
{noformat}
          @Before
	  @Override
	  public void setUp() throws Exception {
	    super.setUp();
	  }
{noformat}
This method does nothing, can be removed.

